00:00:03.269 --> 00:00:04.637
&gt;&gt; David: Travel nightmares.

00:00:04.637 --> 00:00:06.139
&gt;&gt; Oh, our flight was
cancelled this morning

00:00:06.139 --> 00:00:08.241
with basically no notice.

00:00:08.241 --> 00:00:10.043 align:start size:84% position:16%
&gt;&gt; David: Delayed,
cancelled, stranded...

00:00:10.043 --> 00:00:13.212 align:start position:0%
Will a Passenger Bill of Rights
always protect you?

00:00:13.212 --> 00:00:14.680
&gt;&gt; If it's supposed to be
a passenger charter then

00:00:14.680 --> 00:00:15.849
make it for the passengers.

00:00:17.016 --> 00:00:18.684
&gt;&gt; David: Canada versus Europe.

00:00:18.684 --> 00:00:21.287
If you'd been on the same
plane leaving from Europe,

00:00:21.287 --> 00:00:22.855
they would owe you
hundreds of dollars.

00:00:22.855 --> 00:00:23.856
&gt;&gt; That's--

00:00:23.856 --> 00:00:24.857
that's really annoying.

00:00:24.857 --> 00:00:26.726
&gt;&gt; David: We're chasing
the people with power.

00:00:26.726 --> 00:00:31.797
If an airline isn't fined when
they break the rules then why

00:00:31.797 --> 00:00:33.232
should they follow the rules?

00:00:33.232 --> 00:00:35.368
It's fight, or flight time!

00:00:35.368 --> 00:00:37.336
This is your Marketplace.

00:00:37.336 --> 00:00:39.239
[ ♪♪ ]

00:00:46.579 --> 00:00:47.747
&gt;&gt; David: At the
Toronto airport,

00:00:47.747 --> 00:00:50.783
I'm checking in to
check up on airlines.

00:00:50.783 --> 00:00:52.685
[ ♪♪ ]

00:00:58.557 --> 00:01:00.493 align:start size:91% position:9%
&gt;&gt; David: Passenger
complaints are on the rise

00:01:00.493 --> 00:01:04.931 align:start size:94% position:6%
in Canada, so we want to
test your rights on flights.

00:01:10.003 --> 00:01:11.271
What's your biggest
beef when flying?

00:01:12.605 --> 00:01:14.206 align:start size:81% position:19%
&gt;&gt; Delays.
Been delayed a lot.

00:01:14.206 --> 00:01:16.041
Yeah, um...

00:01:16.041 --> 00:01:17.042 align:start size:88% position:13%
&gt;&gt; Lost luggage.
&gt;&gt; David: Lost luggage?

00:01:17.042 --> 00:01:18.778 align:start size:75% position:25%
&gt;&gt; Lost luggage.
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:01:18.778 --> 00:01:19.779 align:start size:88% position:13%
&gt;&gt; We had our
flight cancelled, yeah.

00:01:19.779 --> 00:01:21.581 align:start size:84% position:16%
&gt;&gt; David: Uh-oh.
No matter the airline,

00:01:21.581 --> 00:01:23.883 align:start size:81% position:19%
it seems everyone's
had problems.

00:01:23.883 --> 00:01:28.153
Have you ever been
delayed on a flight?

00:01:28.153 --> 00:01:29.288 align:start size:75% position:25%
&gt;&gt; Yes!
&gt;&gt; All the time.

00:01:29.288 --> 00:01:30.289 align:start size:84% position:16%
&gt;&gt; We've been delayed.
&gt;&gt; David: Really?

00:01:30.289 --> 00:01:31.290 align:start size:75% position:25%
&gt;&gt; Yeah?
&gt;&gt; David: What?

00:01:31.290 --> 00:01:32.725
How long?

00:01:32.725 --> 00:01:34.393 align:start size:78% position:22%
&gt;&gt; Hours.
&gt;&gt; David: Hours?!

00:01:34.393 --> 00:01:35.994
You ever get
flight delays?

00:01:35.994 --> 00:01:37.630
&gt;&gt; Yes, about 40% of the time.

00:01:37.630 --> 00:01:39.498
&gt;&gt; David: 40% of the time.

00:01:39.498 --> 00:01:41.500
Long delays are a big beef.

00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:43.602
Just ask Chris Conrad.

00:01:43.602 --> 00:01:44.803
[ ♪♪ ]

00:01:44.803 --> 00:01:50.143
&gt;&gt; I'm tired and frustrated
and I just want to get going.

00:01:50.143 --> 00:01:52.912 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; David: That's how Chris felt
when her European vacation

00:01:52.912 --> 00:01:55.848
was delayed by nearly a day.

00:01:55.848 --> 00:01:58.751
She says they didn't board
until one in the morning.

00:02:00.553 --> 00:02:02.188
&gt;&gt; David: And still
there's more delay.

00:02:02.188 --> 00:02:03.689 align:start size:78% position:22%
&gt;&gt; More delay,
and we sat around,

00:02:03.689 --> 00:02:04.857
and we sat around and...

00:02:04.857 --> 00:02:08.127 align:start position:0%
It was a really old rickety kind
of plane and when they tried

00:02:08.127 --> 00:02:10.229 align:start size:88% position:13%
to close the door it
wouldn't close properly.

00:02:10.229 --> 00:02:12.065 align:start size:78% position:22%
And then we sat
there for a while,

00:02:12.065 --> 00:02:16.135
and then they taxied out a bit,
and then they taxied back again.

00:02:16.135 --> 00:02:17.470
Well, they said, "Oh,
the original plane was

00:02:17.470 --> 00:02:19.805
"broken so we had to get
this other old plane in,

00:02:19.805 --> 00:02:22.275
"and they put a new
engine in it, and now

00:02:22.275 --> 00:02:23.943
the engine isn't working."

00:02:23.943 --> 00:02:26.178 align:start size:81% position:19%
So, they were
trying to fix that.

00:02:26.178 --> 00:02:28.781 align:start size:88% position:13%
&gt;&gt; David: That
costs three more hours.

00:02:28.781 --> 00:02:30.282 align:start size:81% position:19%
That's a long time.
&gt;&gt; It is.

00:02:30.282 --> 00:02:31.817
It is, yeah.

00:02:31.817 --> 00:02:33.786 align:start size:94% position:6%
&gt;&gt; David: You must have
been going just stir crazy.

00:02:33.786 --> 00:02:35.287
&gt;&gt; I was hungry, and I was
tired, and I was thirsty,

00:02:35.287 --> 00:02:37.990 align:start size:78% position:22%
and I just wanted
to go home.

00:02:37.990 --> 00:02:40.526
&gt;&gt; David: Air Canada
does send her home...

00:02:40.526 --> 00:02:41.627
..in a taxi.

00:02:41.627 --> 00:02:45.064
After an overnight delay
her flight is cancelled,

00:02:45.064 --> 00:02:47.700 align:start size:88% position:13%
and she's booked to
fly the following night.

00:02:47.700 --> 00:02:51.037
Total delay, 22 hours.

00:02:51.037 --> 00:02:53.539 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; They should have their
planes in good working order.

00:02:53.539 --> 00:02:56.008 align:start size:91% position:9%
They robbed me of an
entire day of my vacation.

00:02:56.008 --> 00:02:58.144
I didn't sleep for 48 hours.

00:02:58.144 --> 00:03:02.948 align:start size:94% position:6%
I think they owe me at least
half of my air fare back.

00:03:02.948 --> 00:03:05.985
&gt;&gt; David: So, she asks for it.

00:03:05.985 --> 00:03:08.621
And what did Air Canada give
you in the way of compensation?

00:03:08.621 --> 00:03:13.993
&gt;&gt; They offered me 25% off
in undiscounted base fare.

00:03:13.993 --> 00:03:15.494
&gt;&gt; David: How much is that?

00:03:15.494 --> 00:03:18.297 align:start size:84% position:16%
Well, take away all
the extra fees and the

00:03:18.297 --> 00:03:21.401
base fare is just $329.

00:03:21.401 --> 00:03:23.302
25% off that?

00:03:23.302 --> 00:03:26.472
$82.25.

00:03:26.472 --> 00:03:28.474
Not good enough for Chris.

00:03:28.474 --> 00:03:30.576 align:start size:91% position:9%
&gt;&gt; It's like a slap in the
face, really, you know?

00:03:30.576 --> 00:03:32.712
It's like they--they don't care.

00:03:32.712 --> 00:03:34.647
&gt;&gt; David: But they don't
actually owe her anything.

00:03:34.647 --> 00:03:37.650
Under the existing rules,
travelers like Chris have

00:03:37.650 --> 00:03:41.320 align:start size:97% position:3%
no clear right to compensation
from any Canadian airline.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:45.257
But there might be
hope in the future...

00:03:45.257 --> 00:03:47.926
because the rules
could be changing.

00:03:47.926 --> 00:03:49.829
[ ♪♪ ]

00:03:51.296 --> 00:03:54.000 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; David: Minister Of Transport,
Marc Garneau.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:58.670
&gt;&gt; We're here to make sure that
passengers rights are respected.

00:03:58.670 --> 00:04:00.072 align:start size:84% position:16%
&gt;&gt; David: Last spring,
he announced a

00:04:00.072 --> 00:04:02.008
Passenger Bill of Rights.

00:04:02.008 --> 00:04:05.778 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; When Canadians buy an
airline ticket they expect the

00:04:05.778 --> 00:04:08.814
airline to keep its
part of the deal.

00:04:08.814 --> 00:04:12.485
&gt;&gt; David: He promises it
will make things better.

00:04:12.485 --> 00:04:13.919
How much better?

00:04:13.919 --> 00:04:16.989 align:start size:81% position:19%
That's what we
intend to find out.

00:04:16.989 --> 00:04:18.891
[ ♪♪ ]

00:04:20.860 --> 00:04:23.095 align:start size:84% position:16%
&gt;&gt; David: We're at
the Halifax airport...

00:04:23.095 --> 00:04:24.397 align:start size:72% position:28%
Hi, Gabor.
&gt;&gt; Hey, David.

00:04:24.397 --> 00:04:27.366
&gt;&gt; David: ..to meet a guy who
knows all about the new rules.

00:04:27.366 --> 00:04:29.335 align:start size:78% position:22%
Shall we go chat?
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:04:29.335 --> 00:04:32.472 align:start size:91% position:9%
&gt;&gt; David: Passenger rights
advocate, Gabor Lukacs.

00:04:32.472 --> 00:04:35.307 align:start size:97% position:3%
He fights for disrupted
air travelers seeking justice

00:04:35.307 --> 00:04:37.643
from any airline.

00:04:37.643 --> 00:04:42.014 align:start size:94% position:6%
In the case of Chris,
would the new bill mean that

00:04:42.014 --> 00:04:43.449
she would get compensation?

00:04:43.449 --> 00:04:45.751
&gt;&gt; Under new bill, she would
not get compensation either.

00:04:45.751 --> 00:04:49.922 align:start size:94% position:6%
The bill exonerates airlines
from the obligation to

00:04:49.922 --> 00:04:53.893 align:start size:88% position:13%
compensate passengers
when the delay is caused

00:04:53.893 --> 00:04:56.028
by mechanical issues.

00:04:56.028 --> 00:04:57.964
[ ♪♪ ]

00:04:57.964 --> 00:05:00.699
&gt;&gt; David: Mechanical problems
are a common reason for delays

00:05:00.699 --> 00:05:02.301
and cancellations.

00:05:02.301 --> 00:05:05.837 align:start position:0%
But here's the thing, even under
minister Garneau's new rules,

00:05:05.837 --> 00:05:09.207
passengers like Chris
won't get compensation.

00:05:09.207 --> 00:05:11.577
And Lukacs says that's wrong.

00:05:11.577 --> 00:05:15.348
&gt;&gt; Airlines should be liable for
compensating passengers in the

00:05:15.348 --> 00:05:18.517
event of cancellation, delay,
or overbooking that is somehow

00:05:18.517 --> 00:05:21.554
caused by mechanical issues.

00:05:21.554 --> 00:05:22.788
That's a no brainer.

00:05:22.788 --> 00:05:25.791
That has been the rule in Europe
and I don't see why it should be

00:05:25.791 --> 00:05:27.193
any different in Canada.

00:05:27.193 --> 00:05:31.230
&gt;&gt; David: So, what are
those European rules?

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:33.699
To find out we've
come to England.

00:05:33.699 --> 00:05:35.601 align:start size:94% position:6%
[ British Anthem
"God Save The Queen" Plays ]

00:05:37.269 --> 00:05:38.371 align:start size:81% position:19%
&gt;&gt; David: Travelers
here have had a

00:05:38.371 --> 00:05:41.707 align:start size:88% position:13%
Passenger Bill of Rights
since 2005.

00:05:41.707 --> 00:05:45.344 align:start position:0%
They're entitled to compensation
when things go wrong,

00:05:45.344 --> 00:05:49.182 align:start position:0%
even when most
mechanical issues are to blame.

00:05:54.587 --> 00:05:56.555
But here's the thing
many people don't know.

00:05:56.555 --> 00:05:59.525 align:start size:97% position:3%
It was a fight to get those
rights so we're heading to the

00:05:59.525 --> 00:06:04.262
north of England to meet
the man behind that fight.

00:06:04.262 --> 00:06:06.165
[ ♪♪ ]

00:06:13.939 --> 00:06:15.007 align:start size:81% position:19%
&gt;&gt; David: Hi, Coby.
&gt;&gt; Hi, David.

00:06:15.007 --> 00:06:16.008 align:start size:91% position:9%
Welcome to Birmingham.
&gt;&gt; David: Yeah, thank you.

00:06:16.008 --> 00:06:17.043
I'm David.

00:06:17.043 --> 00:06:20.246
Coby Benson calls himself
a flight delay lawyer.

00:06:21.781 --> 00:06:23.116 align:start size:88% position:13%
Alright.
Quite a few people here.

00:06:23.116 --> 00:06:24.116
&gt;&gt; That's right.

00:06:24.116 --> 00:06:25.751 align:start size:81% position:19%
We have a team
of about 20 people.

00:06:25.751 --> 00:06:27.820
&gt;&gt; David: His firm's
built a business out of

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:30.890
flight disruptions, helping
clients get the compensation

00:06:30.890 --> 00:06:32.758
they're entitled to.

00:06:32.758 --> 00:06:35.995
&gt;&gt; There's tens of thousands
of people every single year

00:06:35.995 --> 00:06:38.397
who have had their claims
denied by the airlines.

00:06:38.397 --> 00:06:39.465
They come to us.

00:06:39.465 --> 00:06:41.700 align:start size:84% position:16%
&gt;&gt; David: And one
precedent setting case

00:06:41.700 --> 00:06:44.803 align:start size:88% position:13%
put them on the map
when a European carrier

00:06:44.803 --> 00:06:49.575
used mechanical malfunction
as a reason to deny a claim,

00:06:49.575 --> 00:06:51.844
Coby took it to court.

00:06:51.844 --> 00:06:54.213
The airlines' legal
argument didn't fly.

00:06:54.213 --> 00:06:56.815
&gt;&gt; The real legal test as
confirmed by the court,

00:06:56.815 --> 00:06:59.218
was whether it's out of the
ordinary and quite simply the

00:06:59.218 --> 00:07:00.986
court said that these
technical problems are

00:07:00.986 --> 00:07:03.355
not out of the ordinary.

00:07:03.355 --> 00:07:05.791 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; David: For an airline to
avoid paying they have to prove

00:07:05.791 --> 00:07:08.961 align:start size:91% position:9%
the reason for disruption
was extraordinary.

00:07:08.961 --> 00:07:11.964 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; Thankfully, we were
successful in arguing that most

00:07:11.964 --> 00:07:14.500 align:start position:0%
technical problems are not
extraordinary and therefore the

00:07:14.500 --> 00:07:15.735
airlines have to pay out.

00:07:15.735 --> 00:07:16.936 align:start size:78% position:22%
It was a great
victory for us....

00:07:16.936 --> 00:07:19.738 align:start size:97% position:3%
It was an enormous battle
against a very large airline.

00:07:19.738 --> 00:07:23.208 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; David: So, now as a result,
anyone flying on a European

00:07:23.208 --> 00:07:27.012 align:start size:88% position:13%
airline can claim for
most flight disruptions.

00:07:27.012 --> 00:07:31.583
Even Canadian airlines have
to follow the same rules when

00:07:31.583 --> 00:07:33.352
flying out of Europe.

00:07:33.352 --> 00:07:36.789 align:start size:94% position:6%
So, how would that
affect Chris' 22-hour delay?

00:07:38.390 --> 00:07:40.092 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; If she was flying from Europe
to Canada, it wouldn't have

00:07:40.092 --> 00:07:42.561
mattered which airline she was
on, she would've been covered

00:07:42.561 --> 00:07:45.464
under European law, even though
she's not a European citizen,

00:07:45.464 --> 00:07:47.867 align:start size:91% position:9%
and then she would've been
entitled to 600 Euros--

00:07:47.867 --> 00:07:50.636 align:start size:94% position:6%
&gt;&gt; David: 600 Euros.
That's about $900 Canadian.

00:07:50.636 --> 00:07:51.737
That's a lot of money.

00:07:51.737 --> 00:07:53.238 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; That's right, it's a lot of
money, and a passenger

00:07:53.238 --> 00:07:55.507 align:start size:94% position:6%
only needs to have been
delayed three or maybe four

00:07:55.507 --> 00:07:58.444 align:start size:88% position:13%
hours in order to get
that large sum of money.

00:07:58.444 --> 00:08:00.746
&gt;&gt; David: We break
that news to Chris.

00:08:00.746 --> 00:08:04.083
If you'd been on the same
plane leaving from Europe,

00:08:04.083 --> 00:08:05.684
they would owe you
hundreds of dollars.

00:08:05.684 --> 00:08:07.186
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:08:07.186 --> 00:08:08.420
That's--

00:08:08.420 --> 00:08:10.122
that's really annoying.

00:08:10.122 --> 00:08:11.723
It's--it's not fair.

00:08:11.723 --> 00:08:12.959
&gt;&gt; David: Do you have
any words of advice for

00:08:12.959 --> 00:08:15.227
Canadian passengers?

00:08:15.227 --> 00:08:18.230
&gt;&gt; If they're flying to Europe
make sure you're flying with a

00:08:18.230 --> 00:08:20.966
European carrier and you'll be
protected under the very strong

00:08:20.966 --> 00:08:24.804
and pro-consumer European law.

00:08:24.804 --> 00:08:27.439 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; David: Europeans have
become used to the protection

00:08:27.439 --> 00:08:31.343
but don't always realize
that not everyone has it.

00:08:31.343 --> 00:08:33.345 align:start size:91% position:9%
In Canada, we don't
have those kind of rules.

00:08:33.345 --> 00:08:34.447 align:start size:81% position:19%
&gt;&gt; Yeah, okay.
&gt;&gt; David: Does that

00:08:34.447 --> 00:08:35.714
surprise you at all?

00:08:35.714 --> 00:08:37.483
&gt;&gt; It does, yeah because...

00:08:37.483 --> 00:08:39.251 align:start size:91% position:9%
I kind of think of Canada
as a very, sort of,

00:08:39.251 --> 00:08:43.122 align:start size:91% position:9%
consumer rights kind of--
kind of society.

00:08:43.122 --> 00:08:45.591 align:start size:94% position:6%
&gt;&gt; So, what circumstances
will they have to compensate

00:08:45.591 --> 00:08:47.993 align:start size:94% position:6%
passengers if it's not
mechanical or weather then?

00:08:47.993 --> 00:08:49.795
What else is left?

00:08:49.795 --> 00:08:50.929
[ Laughter ]

00:08:50.929 --> 00:08:54.099 align:start size:81% position:19%
&gt;&gt; What say you
Canadian government?

00:08:54.099 --> 00:08:55.634
&gt;&gt; If it's supposed to be
a passenger charter then

00:08:55.634 --> 00:08:57.136
make it for the passengers.

00:08:57.136 --> 00:08:59.038
[ Speaking French ]

00:09:03.042 --> 00:09:04.643
&gt;&gt; David: Okay.
So, there you go.

00:09:04.643 --> 00:09:07.679
The Frenchman says that we
in  Canada either should have

00:09:07.679 --> 00:09:10.816 align:start size:88% position:13%
a revolution or a strike
to get these rights.

00:09:11.516 --> 00:09:12.652
[ Bells Ringing ]

00:09:15.087 --> 00:09:17.823 align:start size:94% position:6%
&gt;&gt; David: Gabor Lukacs
is fighting for those rights

00:09:17.823 --> 00:09:19.325
in Parliament.

00:09:19.325 --> 00:09:22.795 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; For the all too common
event of mechanical malfunction,

00:09:22.795 --> 00:09:26.265 align:start size:97% position:3%
the bill proposes to actually
relieve airlines from the

00:09:26.265 --> 00:09:29.334 align:start size:97% position:3%
obligation to compensate
passengers for inconvenience.

00:09:29.334 --> 00:09:31.703
&gt;&gt; David: He's invited to
share his concerns with a

00:09:31.703 --> 00:09:34.974
House Of Commons committee
that's reviewing the bill.

00:09:34.974 --> 00:09:37.043
&gt;&gt; We recommend that the
committee amend paragraph

00:09:37.043 --> 00:09:41.613 align:start size:94% position:6%
86.11 Sub 1 Sub B to
clarify that in the event of

00:09:41.613 --> 00:09:45.116
mechanical malfunctions,
airlines are liable to

00:09:45.116 --> 00:09:47.420 align:start size:88% position:13%
compensate passengers
for their inconvenience.

00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:49.888
&gt;&gt; David: It's going to be
an uphill fight for Lukacs.

00:09:49.888 --> 00:09:51.923 align:start size:81% position:19%
But these passengers
are on his side.

00:09:51.923 --> 00:09:53.592
[ ♪♪ ]

00:09:53.592 --> 00:09:54.694 align:start size:84% position:16%
&gt;&gt; I mean, they really
should change it.

00:09:54.694 --> 00:09:56.795 align:start size:91% position:9%
It holds them accountable
as an airline, right?

00:09:56.795 --> 00:09:57.896
&gt;&gt; David: Do you think
you should be entitled

00:09:57.896 --> 00:09:59.465
to compensation?
&gt;&gt; Oh, absolutely!

00:09:59.465 --> 00:10:01.133
&gt;&gt; Yeah, definitely not
in the best interests of

00:10:01.133 --> 00:10:02.335
customers and flyers.

00:10:05.037 --> 00:10:06.939
&gt;&gt; David: Time to
get some answers...

00:10:10.409 --> 00:10:14.380 align:start size:88% position:13%
..from Marc Garneau,
the man behind the bill.

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:17.649
As it stands now, the bill
does not require airlines to

00:10:17.649 --> 00:10:21.586 align:start position:0%
compensate passengers in the
event of mechanical malfunction.

00:10:21.586 --> 00:10:22.587
Why is that?

00:10:22.587 --> 00:10:24.723
&gt;&gt; Well, what we
have decided to do,

00:10:24.723 --> 00:10:30.563
in some cases if there is an
operational delay in a flight,

00:10:30.563 --> 00:10:34.967
for example because the flight
crew was not there to fly it,

00:10:34.967 --> 00:10:39.638
or the airline made a change for
operational reasons to maximize

00:10:39.638 --> 00:10:41.140
their traffic flow.

00:10:41.140 --> 00:10:42.908
&gt;&gt; David: If they cancelled a
flight because it wasn't full?

00:10:42.908 --> 00:10:45.110
&gt;&gt; There will be compensation
there because that's something

00:10:45.110 --> 00:10:46.311
that is within their control.

00:10:46.311 --> 00:10:48.013
It is not a mechanical problem.

00:10:48.013 --> 00:10:50.249 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; David: But why is mechanical
not within their control?

00:10:50.249 --> 00:10:52.952
&gt;&gt; We do consider it to be
within their control but for

00:10:52.952 --> 00:10:54.653 align:start size:91% position:9%
safety reasons, of course,
we don't want them to

00:10:54.653 --> 00:10:56.121
take off if there is a problem.

00:10:56.121 --> 00:10:58.457
&gt;&gt; David: In Europe they don't
have to choose between safety

00:10:58.457 --> 00:11:00.292
and compensation.
They get both.

00:11:00.292 --> 00:11:02.361
&gt;&gt; We're putting together
our own Bill of Rights and

00:11:02.361 --> 00:11:05.263 align:start size:97% position:3%
I think you're gonna see that
we have a world-leading

00:11:05.263 --> 00:11:08.000
class or category
of compensations.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:09.234
&gt;&gt; David: Let me put
it to you this way,

00:11:09.234 --> 00:11:13.672 align:start size:97% position:3%
if you and I get on a plane
and fly to anywhere in Europe,

00:11:13.672 --> 00:11:16.508 align:start position:0%
if there is a delay, a big delay
from a mechanical malfunction

00:11:16.508 --> 00:11:20.112 align:start size:94% position:6%
on our way back from Europe,
we do get compensation.

00:11:20.112 --> 00:11:23.682
Why should we as air passengers
be treated differently depending

00:11:23.682 --> 00:11:25.584
on which direction
we're flying from?

00:11:25.584 --> 00:11:29.120 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; I think that we have to,
yes, compensate passengers for

00:11:29.120 --> 00:11:32.090
certain things but at the same
time we want to make sure that--

00:11:32.090 --> 00:11:35.427
that our airlines can
remain competitive,

00:11:35.427 --> 00:11:37.830 align:start size:91% position:9%
so they can keep the
prices as low as possible.

00:11:37.830 --> 00:11:40.299 align:start size:94% position:6%
&gt;&gt; David: Some people
feel that airlines have more

00:11:40.299 --> 00:11:43.402
protection than passengers.

00:11:43.402 --> 00:11:47.072 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; I believe that this is very
balanced and that we are

00:11:47.072 --> 00:11:50.309 align:start size:91% position:9%
seriously addressing
the rights of passengers.

00:11:50.309 --> 00:11:53.612 align:start size:91% position:9%
&gt;&gt; David: But it is not
enough for this passenger.

00:11:53.612 --> 00:11:57.449 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; Well, it makes me wonder
whose side the government is on.

00:11:57.449 --> 00:11:59.852
There's no incentive for
them to even have their

00:11:59.852 --> 00:12:01.586
planes on time now.

00:12:01.586 --> 00:12:04.422 align:start size:94% position:6%
If they had to pay everybody
compensation every time

00:12:04.422 --> 00:12:07.426
their planes were delayed or--
I think that would make them

00:12:07.426 --> 00:12:09.160
pull their socks up a bit.

00:12:09.160 --> 00:12:11.463
[ ♪♪ ]

00:12:11.463 --> 00:12:14.667
&gt;&gt; David: Benson agrees that
the rules are a good deterrent.

00:12:14.667 --> 00:12:17.736
&gt;&gt; European rules have
encouraged punctuality of

00:12:17.736 --> 00:12:21.707 align:start size:97% position:3%
airlines, so the law has acted
as a really good mechanism

00:12:21.707 --> 00:12:25.077
to ensure that the airlines
are operating efficiently

00:12:25.077 --> 00:12:26.411
and on time.

00:12:26.411 --> 00:12:29.781
&gt;&gt; David: How this man took
on a major airline and won.

00:12:29.781 --> 00:12:30.950
&gt;&gt; It wasn't about
the money for me.

00:12:30.950 --> 00:12:33.018 align:start size:88% position:13%
It was about just
bringing this to light.

00:12:33.018 --> 00:12:34.186
&gt;&gt; David: Should a
passenger have to go

00:12:34.186 --> 00:12:36.855
to court to get something
that they actually deserve

00:12:36.855 --> 00:12:38.123
under the existing rules?

00:12:38.123 --> 00:12:40.959 align:start position:0%
Fighting For Your Flight Rights
continues...

00:12:40.959 --> 00:12:43.028
only on your Marketplace.

00:12:43.028 --> 00:12:46.064
[ ♪♪ ]

00:12:46.064 --> 00:12:49.701 align:start size:84% position:16%
&gt;&gt; David: It's
fight or flight time.

00:12:49.701 --> 00:12:51.604
[ ♪♪ ]

00:12:57.042 --> 00:12:58.577
&gt;&gt; Oh, our flight was
cancelled this morning

00:12:58.577 --> 00:13:00.845
with basically no notice.

00:13:00.845 --> 00:13:04.049 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; David: No matter the airline,
your frustrations with flying

00:13:04.049 --> 00:13:05.717
are sky high.

00:13:05.717 --> 00:13:09.921
&gt;&gt; There has to be something
that can make some processes

00:13:09.921 --> 00:13:11.990 align:start size:91% position:9%
like this a little easier,
a little better.

00:13:11.990 --> 00:13:14.092 align:start size:94% position:6%
&gt;&gt; David: It can be a
long fight to get the right

00:13:14.092 --> 00:13:16.161
compensation from airlines.

00:13:16.161 --> 00:13:17.663
Most of us just give up.

00:13:22.100 --> 00:13:23.335
[ ♪♪ ]

00:13:23.335 --> 00:13:24.502
&gt;&gt; David: But not this guy.

00:13:24.502 --> 00:13:27.239
He took on Air Canada and won.

00:13:27.239 --> 00:13:28.540 align:start size:81% position:19%
&gt;&gt; David: Hey, Dan?
&gt;&gt; Hi, David?

00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:31.142
&gt;&gt; David: In Fall River,
Nova Scotia, Dan Lachance's

00:13:31.142 --> 00:13:34.179
battle began after a
cross-country journey

00:13:34.179 --> 00:13:37.816
to Whitehorse involving
three connecting flights.

00:13:37.816 --> 00:13:40.285 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; So, when I got to Vancouver
and boarded the flight for

00:13:40.285 --> 00:13:42.688
Whitehorse and we were
just about to take off,

00:13:42.688 --> 00:13:44.156 align:start size:84% position:16%
and we were
seated and belted in,

00:13:44.156 --> 00:13:47.926 align:start position:0%
and then I was asked to deplane,
because there was another

00:13:47.926 --> 00:13:51.296
passenger that had been
ticketed for that seat.

00:13:51.296 --> 00:13:52.665
&gt;&gt; David: And they
come to you and say,

00:13:52.665 --> 00:13:54.366
"You gotta get off."

00:13:54.366 --> 00:13:56.468 align:start size:84% position:16%
&gt;&gt; Yes, that's exactly
what happened.

00:13:56.468 --> 00:13:58.070
It was a shocker.
It was a shocker.

00:13:58.070 --> 00:14:00.772 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; David: Dan was booked
on the next flight which meant

00:14:00.772 --> 00:14:02.808
a delay of nine hours.

00:14:02.808 --> 00:14:05.110
&gt;&gt; I was not happy
with the situation,

00:14:05.110 --> 00:14:06.912 align:start size:88% position:13%
and I wouldn't arrive
there, as it turned out,

00:14:06.912 --> 00:14:08.213
till after midnight.

00:14:08.213 --> 00:14:09.281
[ ♪♪ ]

00:14:09.281 --> 00:14:11.149
&gt;&gt; David: But he
does have rights.

00:14:11.149 --> 00:14:14.052
Air Canada's own rules
say that passengers who

00:14:14.052 --> 00:14:17.656 align:start position:0%
are bumped off a flight,
and then substantially delayed,

00:14:17.656 --> 00:14:20.592
get $800 bucks compensation.

00:14:20.592 --> 00:14:21.827
&gt;&gt; David: Did you get that $800?

00:14:21.827 --> 00:14:22.828
&gt;&gt; No.

00:14:22.828 --> 00:14:24.762 align:start size:91% position:9%
&gt;&gt; David: Dan emails
Air Canada asking for the

00:14:24.762 --> 00:14:27.166
money and receives this reply.

00:14:27.166 --> 00:14:29.300
&gt;&gt; And essentially says
that they sometimes have

00:14:29.300 --> 00:14:30.736
to deny boarding.
&gt;&gt; David: Mmm-hmm.

00:14:30.736 --> 00:14:33.505 align:start size:91% position:9%
&gt;&gt; And so, as a result,
they would offer a %15 off

00:14:33.505 --> 00:14:37.409
the base fare of my next
booking, at aircanada.com.

00:14:37.409 --> 00:14:40.145 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; David: He refuses the
discount and takes Air Canada

00:14:40.145 --> 00:14:41.813
to small claims court.

00:14:41.813 --> 00:14:44.182 align:start size:84% position:16%
That sure gets
their full attention.

00:14:44.182 --> 00:14:45.584
They offer to settle.

00:14:45.584 --> 00:14:46.785
They say here's the money.

00:14:46.785 --> 00:14:49.754
&gt;&gt; Right, but at the same time,
in the same letter, along with

00:14:49.754 --> 00:14:53.058 align:start position:0%
that offer is a declaration that
there's no admission of

00:14:53.058 --> 00:14:54.860
any wrongdoing on
Air Canada's part.

00:14:54.860 --> 00:14:56.228
That was the trigger.

00:14:56.228 --> 00:14:57.463
It wasn't about
the money for me.

00:14:57.463 --> 00:15:00.298 align:start size:88% position:13%
It was about just
bringing this to light.

00:15:00.298 --> 00:15:01.433
[ ♪♪ ]

00:15:01.433 --> 00:15:03.869 align:start size:91% position:9%
&gt;&gt; David: And so,
he gets his day in court.

00:15:03.869 --> 00:15:06.204 align:start size:84% position:16%
But the airline
still won't back down.

00:15:06.204 --> 00:15:08.373 align:start size:94% position:6%
&gt;&gt; The big response from
Air Canada was that I wasn't

00:15:08.373 --> 00:15:11.076
on the flights that
I said I was on.

00:15:11.076 --> 00:15:14.446 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; David: The airline says their
computer showed Dan missed

00:15:14.446 --> 00:15:17.715
a connection, so they gave
away his seat to Whitehorse.

00:15:17.715 --> 00:15:20.118
But he made all of his flights.

00:15:20.118 --> 00:15:21.487
And he could prove it.

00:15:21.487 --> 00:15:22.754 align:start size:88% position:13%
&gt;&gt; 'Cause I had receipts
that put me there,

00:15:22.754 --> 00:15:24.790
to prove that I was there.

00:15:24.790 --> 00:15:28.494
In this case in Vancouver,
I was there for hours prior

00:15:28.494 --> 00:15:30.395 align:start size:88% position:13%
to the boarding of
that flight at the gate.

00:15:30.395 --> 00:15:31.763
Literally, hours.

00:15:31.763 --> 00:15:32.865
&gt;&gt; David: What happened?

00:15:32.865 --> 00:15:34.399
&gt;&gt; Uh, eventually we won.

00:15:34.399 --> 00:15:38.903 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; David: Dan gets the
money, and his court costs too.

00:15:38.903 --> 00:15:40.305
&gt;&gt; Yeah, that was a good moment.

00:15:40.305 --> 00:15:42.975
The adjudicator essentially said
that Air Canada wasn't following

00:15:42.975 --> 00:15:47.979
its own tariff, wasn't treating
its customers with respect until

00:15:47.979 --> 00:15:51.850
they were actually forced by
the hand essentially to do so.

00:15:51.850 --> 00:15:53.318
&gt;&gt; David: But you didn't win
this case because they didn't

00:15:53.318 --> 00:15:56.288
show you respect, you won
because Air Canada didn't

00:15:56.288 --> 00:15:57.689
follow their own rules?

00:15:57.689 --> 00:15:58.757
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:15:58.757 --> 00:16:00.158
Yeah, it's all about just
following the rules that

00:16:00.158 --> 00:16:02.061
are posted there, and not
trying to get out of it.

00:16:03.729 --> 00:16:05.363
&gt;&gt; David: But it's
not just Air Canada.

00:16:05.363 --> 00:16:09.701
Other airlines have also fought
back against passenger claims.

00:16:09.701 --> 00:16:13.271 align:start position:0%
So, how do we know carriers will
always follow the new rules?

00:16:13.271 --> 00:16:16.842 align:start size:97% position:3%
We tell minister Marc Garneau
about Dan's battle.

00:16:16.842 --> 00:16:19.712
Should a passenger have to go
to court to get something that

00:16:19.712 --> 00:16:21.680 align:start size:91% position:9%
they actually deserve
under the existing rules?

00:16:21.680 --> 00:16:24.349
&gt;&gt; Normally that
should not happen.

00:16:24.349 --> 00:16:27.785 align:start size:91% position:9%
I don't expect
passengers going to court.

00:16:27.785 --> 00:16:31.289
I think the rules will be very
clear and I have the feeling

00:16:31.289 --> 00:16:32.691
that the airlines are
going to cooperate.

00:16:32.691 --> 00:16:35.293
&gt;&gt; David: Will you hold
airlines accountable if

00:16:35.293 --> 00:16:36.362
they break the rules?

00:16:36.362 --> 00:16:37.563
&gt;&gt; Absolutely.

00:16:37.563 --> 00:16:39.998 align:start size:84% position:16%
That has always
been the case and the

00:16:39.998 --> 00:16:44.002
Canadian Transportation Agency
which is a semi-judicial body

00:16:44.002 --> 00:16:47.439
has the power to
impose penalties.

00:16:50.375 --> 00:16:54.213
&gt;&gt; The Canadian transportation
agency has failed its mandate.

00:16:54.213 --> 00:16:57.482 align:start size:94% position:6%
It has abdicated its
mandate to enforce the law.

00:16:57.482 --> 00:16:58.817
[ ♪♪ ]

00:16:58.817 --> 00:17:01.220 align:start size:91% position:9%
&gt;&gt; David: Passenger rights
advocate, Gabor Lukacs,

00:17:01.220 --> 00:17:03.422
has lost faith
in the regulator.

00:17:03.422 --> 00:17:06.791 align:start size:88% position:13%
He doesn't believe
the CTA will crackdown.

00:17:06.791 --> 00:17:10.795
&gt;&gt; From my perspective, we can
have the best possible rules and

00:17:10.795 --> 00:17:13.332 align:start size:97% position:3%
laws that you can imagine,
if they are not being enforced

00:17:13.332 --> 00:17:16.167
they're all futile.

00:17:16.167 --> 00:17:18.804
&gt;&gt; David: He worries airlines
might not pay up because the

00:17:18.804 --> 00:17:21.940 align:start size:78% position:22%
CTA hasn't been
dishing out fines.

00:17:21.940 --> 00:17:25.777 align:start position:0%
How many times have you
seen in the past several years,

00:17:25.777 --> 00:17:28.847 align:start position:0%
when an airline has been
found to break their own tariff?

00:17:28.847 --> 00:17:30.682 align:start size:91% position:9%
How many times have
they been fined anything?

00:17:30.682 --> 00:17:32.818 align:start size:81% position:19%
&gt;&gt; Never.
&gt;&gt; David: Not once?

00:17:32.818 --> 00:17:34.319
We check that.

00:17:34.319 --> 00:17:35.554
He's right.

00:17:35.554 --> 00:17:38.556
At the time of this interview,
not even one fine in the last

00:17:38.556 --> 00:17:40.459 align:start size:88% position:13%
five years for breaking
their own rules.

00:17:42.427 --> 00:17:44.496
We take that to the minister.

00:17:44.496 --> 00:17:48.667
If an airline isn't fined
when they break the rules,

00:17:48.667 --> 00:17:52.204 align:start position:0%
then why should they follow
the rules if all they have to do

00:17:52.204 --> 00:17:53.871 align:start size:91% position:9%
is pay the money they
would have paid anyway to

00:17:53.871 --> 00:17:55.374
passengers under their tariffs?

00:17:55.374 --> 00:17:57.609
&gt;&gt; Well, they will have to
pay compensation if they've

00:17:57.609 --> 00:18:02.013 align:start size:97% position:3%
violated a passenger's rights
so that is a penalty that

00:18:02.013 --> 00:18:03.214
they will have to pay.

00:18:03.214 --> 00:18:06.919
If they refuse to do that then
they can be fined by the CTA

00:18:06.919 --> 00:18:10.489
and I'm fully competent--
confident that the CTA

00:18:10.489 --> 00:18:12.223
will exercise that power.

00:18:12.223 --> 00:18:13.891
&gt;&gt; David: Even though they
haven't used the power to

00:18:13.891 --> 00:18:15.193
fine over the past five years?

00:18:15.193 --> 00:18:17.462
&gt;&gt; We're talking about
what's ahead of us now.

00:18:17.462 --> 00:18:20.332 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; David: Funny enough,
a week after our interview the

00:18:20.332 --> 00:18:26.071 align:start size:94% position:6%
CTA announces a huge fine
for Air Transat over this...

00:18:26.071 --> 00:18:29.975
&gt;&gt; ...Who called 9-1-1
from this aircraft...

00:18:29.975 --> 00:18:32.377 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; David: What does this
change for your flight rights?

00:18:32.377 --> 00:18:34.379 align:start size:94% position:6%
So, it's increasing the
amount of time that I should

00:18:34.379 --> 00:18:36.481
be stuck on the tarmac for?

00:18:36.481 --> 00:18:38.917
&gt;&gt; It is mind boggling why.

00:18:38.917 --> 00:18:40.285
It makes no sense to me.

00:18:40.285 --> 00:18:43.488 align:start size:97% position:3%
&gt;&gt; David: The Fight For
Your Flight Rights continues.

00:18:43.488 --> 00:18:45.390
[ ♪♪ ]

00:18:45.390 --> 00:18:49.861 align:start size:91% position:9%
&gt;&gt; David: The real
deal on your Marketplace.

00:18:49.861 --> 00:18:52.864
[ ♪♪ ]

00:18:52.864 --> 00:18:56.101
&gt;&gt; David: New passenger rights
are getting ready for takeoff.

00:18:56.101 --> 00:18:58.370
They'll offer you
better protections,

00:18:58.370 --> 00:19:01.239 align:start size:97% position:3%
including banning all airlines
from bumping people

00:19:01.239 --> 00:19:03.542
off a plane against their will.

00:19:03.542 --> 00:19:05.711
&gt;&gt; Oh, my God.

00:19:05.711 --> 00:19:07.512
No!

00:19:07.512 --> 00:19:10.382
&gt;&gt; David: Like the shocking
example of this man being

00:19:10.382 --> 00:19:13.151 align:start size:88% position:13%
dragged off a
United Airlines flight.

00:19:13.151 --> 00:19:15.620 align:start size:94% position:6%
&gt;&gt; Oh, my God!
Look at what you did to him!

00:19:15.620 --> 00:19:18.289
&gt;&gt; David: And in Canada,
remember those Air Transat

00:19:18.289 --> 00:19:21.760 align:start size:91% position:9%
passengers stuck on
the tarmac for six hours?

00:19:21.760 --> 00:19:24.062
They already had rights.

00:19:24.062 --> 00:19:28.634 align:start position:0%
&gt;&gt; The person who called
9-1-1 from this aircraft please

00:19:28.634 --> 00:19:31.703 align:start size:97% position:3%
present yourself to the
very forward of the aircraft.

00:19:31.703 --> 00:19:32.970
&gt;&gt; David: Quite the ordeal.

00:19:32.970 --> 00:19:37.509
As a result, the airline gets
that fine, nearly $300,000.

00:19:37.509 --> 00:19:38.844
Why?

00:19:38.844 --> 00:19:43.482
It broke the rules.

00:19:43.482 --> 00:19:45.817 align:start position:0%
Under the existing rules,
passengers on Canadian airlines

00:19:45.817 --> 00:19:49.588
are entitled to refreshments
and the opportunity to get off

00:19:49.588 --> 00:19:52.056
if they've been stuck on
the tarmac for 90 minutes

00:19:52.056 --> 00:19:54.459
or more so long as it's safe.

00:19:54.459 --> 00:19:57.696 align:start size:94% position:6%
But under the proposed
legislation that time would

00:19:57.696 --> 00:20:02.401
extend to three hours for all
airlines, doubling it from

00:20:02.401 --> 00:20:04.769
just the 90 minutes.

00:20:04.769 --> 00:20:07.039
Consumer advocate,
Gabor Lukacs tried to

00:20:07.039 --> 00:20:08.940
fight that too.

